segments.text: If students didn't feel themselves directly threatened by a governmental activity or policy, they were less likely to be involved in it.
It makes one wonder whether if they hadn't been drafting 18-year-old males or 19-year-old males during the Vietnam War, if we'd have even been able to get that much activity out of students.
In other words, I guess my point is, on the one hand, I think I was disappointed with the way students had changed.
On the other hand, maybe they hadn't changed.
Maybe the only difference was that, you know, people weren't being drafted anymore.
And so there wasn't any, nothing was going to happen to them.
And they were just much more apathetic.
In fact, the only issue that seemed to upset students was the issue of beer drinking on campus or the age at which you could drink alcohol.
And that seemed to draw out a lot of people.
And it was fairly frustrating because we tried to get a student elected to the city council and almost succeeded, got them into a run-on.
That was back when I came back in 1973 to San Marcos.
Our history class was discussing the 50s was back to normalcy and then the 60s
was this anti-war movement type era.
And we were discussing how the late 70s and early 80s, you could describe our era if you were writing 15 years from now, that they all laid back and took a nap.
How do you feel about that?
Do you see that in the students and younger generation today?
Well, I see a lot of, it doesn't seem to be the same degree of activism or concern about what's going on around them.
and I don't know if that's because things are basically fairly peaceful or in the sense there's not anything that's really threatening to the students or college-age students.

I know myself, my father was in the Air Force and my uncle was in the Navy and I have never heard anything while they were in the service, neither one of them went to Vietnam, but I've never heard anything about the service or when they were growing up how they felt at this time.
Do you think that
A lot of people have become a little hush-hush about the 60s, and that's why we don't have some of the feelings that we could have if they had discussed that with us more.
I think a lot of people choose not to discuss it.
Some of it's because they realize that the Vietnam policies that a lot of them supported were really just not correct, and that a lot of people realize that we should never have been there.
And it seemed like as time went on, more and more people agreed that
you know, Vietnam was just a disaster and we should have never been there in the first place.

And I think that's part of it that you don't hear very much about it because most people don't like to either say, you know, we were wrong or we should have done something more to get our government out of there.
Also, I think people just would like to forget that that ever happened.
And it's just not discussed as much anymore.
It's just looked upon as a bad part of the history, and hopefully it won't ever happen again.
Oh, boy.
Well, that's all I have to ask of you.
I really appreciate your time.
I know you probably have a very busy schedule.
That's right.
So, thank you.
Okay.
